    "Sottotitolo": "tracce",
    "Titolo": "Literary Quotes in the Barrio <br>de las Letras <br>Madrid's Literary Quarter",
     "Image": "Immagini/tracce/traccia_3.png",
    "Descrizione": "<p>‘El Barrio de las Letras’ is a central neighbourhood of Madrid well-known, as the former home of writers of the Spanish Golden Age. In recent years this quarter has rendered homage to Spanish literature by adorning Huertas street with quotations from some the most recognized writers who lived here. This quotation references the play Don Juan Tenorio by José de Zorrilla, one of the most remarkable writers of Spanish Romanticism movement. Passing along the street, the floating words serve as permanent homage to the author and a quick glance through the greatest Spanish literature.<br></p>",
    "Descrizione2": "<p style='font-size:18px;font-style: italic;'>The ‘Barrio de las Letras’ is a neighbourhood filled with literature all around its streets reflecting the lives of the writers who once lived in it. Today, inscribed on the pavement, Huertas street showcases quotations from works of some of these writers. The decision to populate the streets with literary quotations was taken by the Ministry of Development in order to render homage to these writers and create a sense of collective identity.  The inclusion of quotations was part of a larger urban reform taking place in 2002 with the intention to revitalise and pedestrianise the quarter so that it could become one of the cultural landmarks in Madrid.<br>In addition to the passage from Don Juan Tenorio by José de Zorrilla (who was known to frequent the Romanticism Café in the neighbourhood), we can see the quotations from some of the greatest writers of Spanish Golden Age, such as Cervantes, Lope de Vega, Góngora, Quevedo all of whom lived and worked here at some point of their careers. Also, the inscription of Benito Perez Galdós recalls the locations of his stories, most centred in Madrid.<br>Everything in the neighbourhood resonates literature—from the Plaza Santa Ana, where the Spanish Theatre stands flanked by two sculptures of Calderón de la Barca and Federico Garcia Lorca, to the house-museums of Lope de Vega and Cervantes. Due to the literary activity that took part in these streets during the Spanish Golden Age, the first Corrales de Comedia of Madrid were installed here.<br>Today the “Barrio de las Letras” echoes its glorious past with the inscriptions and plaques set on the streets, but also through the enthusiastic cultural activities and organizations taking place. The neighbourhood is still the heart of the literary culture of Madrid with numerous theatres, cultural centres and literary cafes. </p>",
    "Dati_box": "<p style='font-size:18px;'><b>Location:</b> Spain, Madrid, Calle de las Huertas<br><b>Materials and Condition: </b>Laton inlay in the pavement<br><b>Date:</b> 2002<br><b>Language:</b> Spanish<br><b>Type of trace:</b> inscription<br><b>Transcription:</b> ¡Ah! ¿No es cierto ángel de amor que en esta apartada orilla más pura la luna brilla y se respira mejor?<br><b>Translation:</b> Oh, my angel of love, do you see that on this secluded shore the moon shines clear and pure and one breathes more easily?</p>",
    "Bibliografia": "<p style='font-size:18px;'><b>Bibliography</b><br>Acosta Morales, Antonio, <i>La remodelación de la calle Huertas</i>, 356 (2004), 26-31<br>García Álvarez, Eva. <i>Inscripciones en el pavimento de la Calle Huertas de Madrid</i>, Ab initio, 3 (2015), 93-115<br>García Henche, Blanca and Salvaj Carrera, Erica <i>Barrios destino. El Barrio de las Letras de Madrid. Creación de una marca destino como estrategia de diferenciación de la oferta de turismo urbano</i>, Estudios turísticos, 215 (2018’) 39 – 60</p>",
    "Crediti": "<p style='font-size:18px;'><b>Credits</b><br><b>Image:</b> Laura Pastor<br><b>Transcription:</b> Laura Pastor<br><b>Translation of TRACE text:</b> N. K. Mayberry and A. S. Kline (The Project Gutenberg EBook)</p>",
    "Autore": "<p align='right'><i>Laura Pastor</i></p>",
